{{moresources|date=July 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Chandrasekharan Nair Stadium | nickname = Police Stadium | image = Chandrashekharan Nair Stadium 2.jpg | caption = Chandrashekaran Nair Stadium | location = [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]] | coordinates = | broke_ground = | opened = 1956 | owner = [[Kerala Police]] Sports & Youth Welfare Society | operator = [[Kerala Police]] Sports & Youth Welfare Society | surface = Grass | construction_cost = | architect = | design-builder = | former_names = | tenants = | seating_capacity = 25,000 }} '''Chandrasekharan Nair Stadium''' is a prominent [[association football|football]] stadium situated in [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]], [[India]].
The stadium, also known as 'Police Stadium', was constructed in honor of the first Inspector General of Police of Kerala Shri.[[ N. Chandrasekharan Nair]] in 1956.<ref>[http://www.keralapolicehistory.com/sprts1.html keralapolicehistory] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031071841/http://www.keralapolicehistory.com/sprts1.html |date=31 October 2011 }}</ref> It hosts both national and international level matches.
The stadium was renovated its existing football ground including clearing and re arranging drains, rearranging the playing arena to accommodate new 6 lane synthetic track, dismantling and renovating the spectator steps as per necessity, turfing, new chain link fencing to the track, provision of structure for score board etc. for 35th National Games. [[File:Palayam View Trivandrum.jpg|thumb|left|A view of CSN stadium (left) and University Stadium (Right)]] [[File:Kalaripayattu demonstration for 35th National Games in Chandrasekharan Nair Stadium Thiruvananthapuram Kerala.jpg|thumb|left|Kalaripayattu demonstration for 35th National Games in Chandrasekharan Nair Stadium Thiruvananthapuram Kerala]]
