{{Infobox ice hockey player |position = [[Defenceman|Defence]] |shoots = Left |catches = |height_ft = 5 |height_in = 6 |weight_lb = 159 |sex = f |ntl_team = RUS |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|2|20}} |birth_place = [[Mozhaysk]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SSR]], [[Soviet Union]] |career_start = 2008 }} {{MedalTableTop}} {{MedalSport | Women's [[ice hockey]]}} {{MedalCountry | {{RUS}} }} {{MedalSport | [[IIHF World Women's Championships]]}} {{MedalBronze | 2013 Ottawa | [[2013 IIHF Women's World Championship|Tournament]]}} {{MedalBottom}}
'''Inna Nikolayevna Dyubanok''' ({{lang-ru|Инна Николаевна Дюбанок}}; born 20 February 1990 in [[Mozhaysk]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]) is a [[Russia]]n [[ice hockey]] [[defense (ice hockey)|defender]].
On December 12, 2017 she and five other Russian hockey players were disqualified with their results at the [[Ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics – Women's tournament|2014 Olympics]] annulled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-sanctions-six-russian-athletes-and-closes-one-case-as-part-of-oswald-commission-findings|title=IOC sanctions six Russian athletes and closes one case as part of the Oswald Commission findingsdate=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 13, 2017|work=olympic.org}}</ref>
==International career== Dyubanok was selected for the [[Russia national women's ice hockey team]] in the [[2010 Winter Olympics]]. She played in all five games, recording one assist.<ref name="2010stats">[http://stats.iihf.com/og2010/IHW400004_83_5_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2010 Olympics]</ref><ref name="IIHFGuide">{{cite book |last=IIHF|title=IIHF Media Guide & Record Book 2012|year=2011 |publisher=Fenn/M&S |page= 550|isbn= 978-0-7710-9598-6}}</ref>
Dyubanok has also appeared for Russia at five [[IIHF Women's World Championship]]s, Her first appearance came in [[2008 IIHF Women's World Championship|2008]]. She was a member of the team that won a bronze medal at the [[2013 IIHF Women's World Championship]].<ref name="2008stats">[https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/138/IHW1380RUS_83_4_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2008 World Championship]</ref><ref name="2009stats">[https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/178/IHW1780RUS_83_4_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2009 World Championship]</ref><ref name="2011stats">[https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/252/IHW2520RUS_83_6_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2011 World Championship]</ref><ref name="2012stats">[https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/271/IHW2710RUS_83_5_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2012 World Championship]</ref><ref name="2013stats">[http://stats.worldwomen2013.com/Hydra/339/IHW3390RUS_83_7_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2013 World Championship] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203030701/http://stats.worldwomen2013.com/Hydra/339/IHW3390RUS_83_7_0.pdf |date=2014-02-03 }}</ref>
She also competed in one junior tournament for the [[Russia women's national under-18 ice hockey team]], playing in the inaugural event in [[2008 IIHF World Women's U18 Championship|2008]].<ref name="2008u18stats">[https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/156/IHW1560RUS_83_5_0.pdf IIHF – Team Russia Stats – 2008 World Championship Under-18]</ref>
